        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Maser lines exhibit line narrowing because the exponential gain factor that amplifies the emission is largest near the line center, where the optical depth is maximum.  At 22 GHz the typical linewidth of individual components is approximately 1.5 km/s, though some unsaturated lines can be as narrow as 1 km/s.  To spectrally resolve these lines, we specify a channel width of 0.5 km/s, which ensures that we have at least two channels across even the narrowest lines.  At this resolution the bandwidth in a single spectral window is limited to &lt;900 km/s, so we are configuring four spectral windows across the sideband.  We have placed four spectral windows in the sideband to cover nearly the full bandwidth available, with contiguous coverage.  Our configuration gives ~3400 km/s of velocity coverage (the 22 GHz lines span ~2000 km/s).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We do not have any angular resolution restrictions on our observations, as the masers are point sources even at sub-milliarcsecond scales.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 321 GHz water masers in the Circinus galaxy (from Hagiwara et al. 2013) are ~30 times weaker than its 22 GHz emission.  If the masers in NGC 4258 show a similar ratio, then we can expect the 321 GHz systemic features to peak at around 60 mJy, while the strongest high-velocity (redshifted) features will peak at ~20 mJy.  We thus request an RMS of 3.5 mJy per spectral line (i.e., per 1 km/s, or per approximately 2 channels).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We stress that ALMA is the only facility currently capable of making this observation.  Although NGC 4258 sits at a high declination, it remains above 15 degrees elevation for ~4 hours per day.  In this proposal we are not aiming for imaging, only a spectrum, so the loss of UV coverage that arises from observing a low-elevation source is not an issue.  Though the masers will be point sources at even the highest resolution that ALMA can achieve, the low elevation of the target means that we'd like to observe with at least a modestly extended configuration, to minimize antenna shadowing.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_LOW_MAX_ELEVATION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Maximizing velocity coverage is critical to our science, since our aim is to detect gas closer to the black hole (and therefore orbiting at a higher velocity) than the 22 GHz water lines.  Our specified channel width is chosen to be able to resolve the narrow, isolated maser lines (with typical linewidths of &lt;~2 km/s) often associated with maser flaring.  These simultaneous requirements drive the high data rate.

If this data rate is prohibitive, we would be willing to apply spectral averaging to reduce the data size. The primary science goals would still be achievable with ~1.5 km/s or even ~2 km/s averaging.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
