    <prp:abstract>Motivated by the recent ALMA detection of 321 GHz water maser emission from the Circinus galaxy (Hagiwara et al. 2013) and ESO 558-G009 (ALMA Cycle 2 proposal 2013.1.0824.S; PI: Braatz), we propose to search for 321 GHz masers from the prototypical maser disk galaxy, NGC 4258.   NGC 4258 has the nearest and brightest 22 GHz megamaser in a "clean" Keplerian disk, making it the best galaxy for exploring the physical conditions in the parsec-scale accretion disk around an AGN.  The disk dynamics have already been established from 22 GHz observations, so by detecting 321 GHz emission in the disk we can uniquely assign to each maser line a radial location within the disk (using the spectrum alone; i.e., no mapping is necessary), which will allow us to probe the physical conditions in the disk as a function of radius.  Although NGC 4258 is a northern target, ALMA is by far the best telescope to conduct this observation.  We are aiming for a sensitivity of 3.5 mJy RMS per 1 km/s channel, which the OT predicts will take less than 4 hours of telescope time.</prp:abstract>
